{"id":"1611.06137","submitter":"Peter Topping","authors":"Miles Simon and Peter M. Topping","title":"Local control on the geometry in 3D Ricci flow","comments":"Minor updates in order to integrate with arXiv:1706.09490 prior to\n  being submitted","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.DG math.AP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The geometry of a ball within a Riemannian manifold is coarsely controlled if\nit has a lower bound on its Ricci curvature and a positive lower bound on its\nvolume. We prove that such coarse local geometric control must persist for a\ndefinite amount of time under three-dimensional Ricci flow, and leads to local\nC/t decay of the full curvature tensor, irrespective of what is happening\nbeyond the local region.\n  As a by-product, our results generalise the Pseudolocality theorem of\nPerelman and Tian-Wang in this dimension by not requiring the Ricci curvature\nto be almost-positive, and not asking the volume growth to be almost-Euclidean.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 18 Nov 2016 16:02:26 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 30 Jun 2017 15:42:11 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-07-03"}
